e were in school, most of my classes were about 25-30ish kids, with one teacher, and it seemed to go well. We didn't have the now so prevalent teacher's aides either. Sometimes it's good for children to learn within a less individualized setting. &#10;I was a public school teacher for 8 years. I was in the trenches, it has nothing to do with a teacher being able to do their job or not. My job is to educate the kids that show up in my classroom. I have taught 30 Kindergarteners with no aid and done a damn good job, but I do not blame nor am I offended by a parent that prefers to keep their child at home and educate them themselves. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="932" language="en" documentId="544" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="runningcomeback13" date="09/05/2013" docType="forumpost" origUrl="http://community.babycenter.com/post/a44369503/home_schooling_debate_this_hypothetical?cpg=18" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="544" notes="" title="Home schooling: Debate this hypothetical"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="544"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="545" end="932"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43"/></xmi:XMI>